â€œIt always starts with a memory.â€

For Yasser, flavour development isnâ€™t about formulas - itâ€™s about tasting, experimenting, and trusting instinct. â€œI do it all the time,â€ he says. â€œYou can flip it around - it depends if youâ€™re creating or tasting.â€

Not everything makes it to the menu. He laughs about a batch he loved that didnâ€™t quite land. â€œPeople were just like, â€˜No.â€™ And I was like, â€˜Dude, then send it all to my house.â€™ I literally took it all.â€

That honesty - about trial, error, and personal taste - is what defines how Amore Gelato is built. Every flavour begins somewhere real, even if it ends differently.

caption:
This post came from a place of deep admiration.
We were moved by Uma Pai, an 82 year old cancer survivor, who has been showing up with strength and compassion by supporting a visually impaired runner for years. That quiet courage is what we wanted to honour.
The love this reel received and seeing it reach over 2 million people meant a lot to us. Thank you for amplifying her story.

The intent of the reel was to celebrate the spirit of sport.. the joy of finishing a 3 km run and the far greater joy of a lifetime journey marked by resilience, generosity, and grit at the age of 82, alongside someone who is visually impaired.

That said, we want to sincerely acknowledge where we fell short. We understand how important accuracy is to the @pinkathonindia community and organisers, and we are truly sorry for the way the distance was mentioned. There was no intention to mislead. The distance was shared symbolically, reflecting her life journey rather than an official race detail.

Team Sironaâ¤ï¸

caption:
You planted the idea. And here it is!
 
*drumroll*
 
Introducing the cleanest, yummiest range of plant protein. Ever! 
 
Ever since we launched our cleanest, lightest whey - so many of you have asked us to do the same for plant protein. And God knows weâ€™ve been trying. God also knows itâ€™s one of the tougher problems heâ€™s given human-kind (easier than Trump though).
 
The problem starts with texture and mouthfeel. Plant protein, by nature, is so chalky and gritty, it can feel like having mud. We feel you.
 
Next comes flavour. Peas, chickpeas, hemp, rice - no matter the source, the grainy taste of the protein has a way of over-powering any other flavor. Of course, as is standard in the food industry, many brands try to solve this by adding â€œnature-identicalâ€ flavours and artificial sweeteners. Which makes the problem worse. Because now it is overly sweet and has that strange, metallic after-taste too.
 
And last, thereâ€™s the question of efficacy. Is plant protein as effective at muscle building as whey? Is it a complete protein? Most plant based sources, standalone, are not.
 
No wonder it took a while nailing this. But we did. Hereâ€™s how.
 
First, we travelled the globe and found a suuuper fine grade of golden pea protein isolate. Aka, very fine particle size to begin with. And hence, much lower chalkiness. BIG WIN!
 
Next, we mixed pea and brown rice protein isolates in a 70:30 ratio. Pea protein is rich in lysine but poor in methionine. Brown rice is the exact opposite. But mix them right, and you get a complete protein. One that has all 9 essential amino acids in the right quantities. YASS!
 
And last, we obviously used real ingredients. Real dark cocoa. Real pista and badaam flakes. Real apple beetroot and carrot (yes, you heard that right!)

It took all this, and a whole lot of trial and error (right sourcing, right recipe proportions, right mixing process, right quality controls) - to make this Clean Plant Protein Actually Tasty.
 
But donâ€™t take our word for it. Try it. Donâ€™t know which flavor to try? Get the All in one sampler and then decide. Use code EASYPEASY and get 10% off. Tell us if it made you go No Whey!

We found out the secret to why your diet soda tastes as sweet as the regular one: Sweetener Blending!

Every sweetener has a sweetness profile. Thatâ€™s the way it tastes and this experience happens in 3 phases: the speed with which it hits you, the mouthfeel, and how long it lingers. This creates a unique curve for every sweetener. The best one? Refined sugar! 

Not all sweeteners have that impact. And brands need to find substitutes that have a similar impact (and keep you coming for more). Thatâ€™s where the scientific technique of Sweetener Blending comes in! They use a combination of different sweeteners to achieve a sweetness curve similar to sugarâ€™s. It tricks your mind into believing youâ€™re having sugar, and gives you that dopamine hit.

When you delay urination, your bladder can become overstretched, which might weaken the bladder muscles over time and potentially lead to urinary incontinence. Additionally, prolonged retention can increase the risk of urinary tract infections (UTIs) because bacteria have more time to grow in the stagnant urine. Holding in pee also puts unnecessary strain on your kidneys, which can lead to kidney infections or other complications.

Itâ€™s important to listen to your bodyâ€™s signals and use the restroom when you need to, to maintain good urinary health and overall well-being.

Hereâ€™s how air pollution can silently worsen menstrual health too:

â€¢ More painful cramps as inflammation levels rise in the body
â€¢ Worsened PMS symptoms like fatigue, mood swings, bloating, and headaches
â€¢ PCOS flare-ups, triggered by increased insulin resistance and hormonal disruption
â€¢ Aggravated endometriosis symptoms due to chronic inflammation
â€¢ Higher stress hormone levels, further throwing cycles off balance
â€¢ Early ovarian ageing, impacting long-term menstrual and fertility health

Menstrual health is often the bodyâ€™s earliest indicator that something isnâ€™t right. When the environment around us is unhealthy, our cycles may be the first to reflect that imbalance.

PMS is a part of the cycle ğŸ’—

The week before your period, known as the luteal phase, can be particularly challenging due to significant hormonal fluctuations. During this time, your body experiences changes in estrogen and progesterone levels, which can lead to a variety of symptoms collectively known as premenstrual syndrome (PMS).

Many people find themselves battling mood swings, irritability, fatigue, and physical discomfort such as bloating and breast tenderness.

These hormonal shifts can amplify stress and emotions, making everyday challenges feel more intense.

Understanding that these symptoms are a natural part of your menstrual cycle can help you manage them more effectively and approach this time with greater self-compassion.

Itâ€™s okay to feel how youâ€™re feeling. Learn about it and take care of yourself.

caption:
Your body warns you before bleeding begins.
.
On day one your uterus releases a chemical called prostaglandins. This chemical makes your uterus squeeze again and again so it can push out the old lining. 

The stronger the squeeze the stronger the pain. That is why you feel cramps back pain and even nausea. 

You may also see white discharge before the bleeding starts because your body is clearing out mucus and leftover lining. 

It is your body doing a lot of work in a very short time and that is why day one always feels the heaviest.

.
If you want to understand your period better and take better care of your body read save and share this.

Youâ€™re Damaging Your Bladder Without Even Realizing It! 
.
Holding in your pee for too long might seem harmless, but it can actually have serious consequences for your health

When you consistently delay urination, your bladder stretches beyond its normal capacity, weakening the muscles over time and making it harder to empty fully

This can lead to urinary tract infections (UTIs), as bacteria have more time to multiply in stagnant urine. In severe cases, prolonged holding can even increase the risk of kidney damage due to the backflow of urine

Ignoring the urge to pee also puts unnecessary pressure on your pelvic floor muscles, which can contribute to long-term bladder control issues

So, instead of waiting until youâ€™re absolutely desperate, listen to your body and take those bathroom breaks youâ€™ll be doing your health a big favor!
.
Tag that friend who always says, â€œIâ€™ll go laterâ€!
.

Periods are natural.
But for years many communities in India and Nepal treated menstruation as something impure.
One of the most extreme examples of this was Chhaupadi a practice that forced girls and women to live in small unsafe huts every time they got their period.

Why did this happen
â€¢ Menstruation was believed to bring bad luck
â€¢ Girls were not allowed inside the house or kitchen
â€¢ They could not touch food water or family members
â€¢ They were left without hygiene products clean clothes or warmth

Research by UNICEF and Human Rights Watch shows that these huts exposed women to
â€¢ Extreme cold or heat
â€¢ Snake bites and wild animals
â€¢ Smoke inhalation
â€¢ Infections from poor hygiene
â€¢ Emotional trauma from isolation

Some cases even led to death.

Chhaupadi has been banned in Nepal but the attitudes that created it still exist in different forms â€” period shame silence restrictions and misinformation.

Understanding this history is important.
It helps us see why menstrual education access and open conversations matter.
No one should ever be punished for a natural biological process.

#MenstrualHealth #PeriodEducation #EndPeriodShame #SironaForChange #BreakTheTaboo

During your period, blood is supposed to flow out of your uterus. But sometimes, some of it flows backward through the fallopian tubes instead.

A Mumbaikar through and through, Anand draws energy from the cityâ€™s rhythm - â€œThereâ€™s something about Mumbaiâ€™s chaos that keeps you grounded,â€ he says. â€œIt reminds you that passion and pace can coexist.â€

PCOS isnâ€™t â€œjust weight gainâ€!
.
Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is one of the most common hormonal disorders among women, yet it often goes unnoticed or undiagnosed. In fact, studies suggest that 1 in 5 women in India may be living with PCOS.
PCOS happens when the ovaries produce higher-than-normal levels of androgens (male hormones), which can interfere with the development and release of eggs during ovulation. This leads to symptoms that show up differently for everyone, but some of the most common include:
âœ¨ Irregular or missed periods
âœ¨ Excess facial or body hair
âœ¨ Persistent acne or oily skin
âœ¨ Sudden weight gain or difficulty losing weight
âœ¨ Thinning scalp hair
âœ¨ Fertility struggles
ğŸ’¡ While there is no â€œone-size-fits-allâ€ cure, PCOS is manageable. A balanced diet, regular exercise, proper sleep, and stress management play a big role in reducing symptoms. In some cases, medication or treatment recommended by a gynecologist/endocrinologist may be necessary.
ğŸŒ± The most important step is awareness. If you experience irregular cycles or other persistent symptoms, donâ€™t ignore them. Early diagnosis not only helps in managing PCOS but also reduces risks of long-term health issues like diabetes, heart problems, or endometrial concerns.
ğŸ’š At Sirona, we believe that every woman deserves to understand her body better and feel empowered to take charge of her health.
#SironaCares #PCOSAwareness #WomensHealth

caption:
First things first: discharge is normal.
.
If you have a vagina, you will have discharge. Itâ€™s your bodyâ€™s way of cleaning, protecting, and keeping things balanced down there. No shame. No panic. No â€œOMG something is wrongâ€ every time you check your underwear.
Now letâ€™s break it down in simple, no-medical-jargon language ğŸ‘‡
1. Clear & stretchy (egg-white like)
This usually shows up around ovulation.
It means: your body is in its fertile phase.
Totally healthy. Totally normal. Often more slippery than usual.
2. White & creamy
Common before or after your period.
It means: everythingâ€™s chill.
As long as thereâ€™s no strong smell, itching, or burningâ€”this is just your vagina being a responsible adult.
3. Thick & white (cottage cheese-like)
This could mean a yeast infection, especially if thereâ€™s itching or redness.
Not dirty. Not your fault. Just your pH being slightly off.
4. Yellow or green
If itâ€™s pale yellow and doesnâ€™t smellâ€”could be normal.
But if itâ€™s greenish, frothy, or smells badâ€”your body is waving a red flag ğŸš©
Time to see a doctor.
5. Grey with a fishy smell
Usually linked to bacterial vaginosis (BV).
Again, common and treatable. Please donâ€™t ignore the smell hoping itâ€™ll â€œfix itself.â€
6. Brown or bloody discharge (when youâ€™re not on your period)
Often old blood leaving the bodyâ€”especially before or after periods.
But if it keeps happening randomly, get it checked.
Important reminder:
Discharge should not come with intense itching, burning, pain, or a strong foul smell. Thatâ€™s your cue to stop Googling and start consulting a professional.
And one last thingâ€”
Your vagina doesnâ€™t need perfumes, harsh washes, or shame.
It needs care, awareness, and honesty.

Knowing whatâ€™s normal for your body is self-care.

Dry vs Dehydrated Skin look similar but behave differently.
Dehydrated skin is a temporary lack of water in the epidermis, and any skin type can be dehydrated. Dry skin is a lack of lipids and sebum production. Skin dryness or roughness is a sign the skin is missing water or lipids or both.

Meet Sumit, Pankil & Abhishek, co-founders of Neighbourhood Hospitality. Theirs is the company behind Woodside Inn, the gastropub that has been serving Mumbai for 18 years. 

Their vision was refreshingly simple: create a space that wasn't pretentious, where people could genuinely enjoy themselves. What started as a single flagship space in Colaba has become a beloved cornerstone of the city's F&B scene; a place where casual meets celebratory, and any hour is the right hour. Eighteen years later, their vision has evolved from "casual and comfortable" to something more profound - timeless. "The sense of 'wow' needs to be sustained," Abhishek reflects, and the proof is in the stories: couples who came on first dates now return with their kids in tow.

Mumbai's identity as a melting pot is something worth celebrating, and the current vibrancy in the F&B space has the boys genuinely excited. They have distinguished dressing preferences; Pankil is a sneakerhead who loves his New Balance kicks and comfort dressing. Sumit balances comfort with polish: tailored button-downs with jeans or chinos. Abhishek loves to travel - so light jackets are his go-to.

"After going to a few Italian places and trying their tiramisu, nothing hit the spot quite like my mother's recipe."

Meet Enrico Signorelli, the mastermind behind Mami Bombay, the tiramisu destination that everyone's raving about. What started as one man's quest for authentic Italian flavours in the city has become a beloved local institution.

A Bergamo, Italy native, Enrico fell in love with Mumbai's incredible food culture during his travels. He loves Indian food, but in his own words: "I have to give my palate a break after a week of Indian food."

Mumbai's spirit of collaboration won him over immediately. "It's lovely how people are willing to help you out," he reflects. The city's energy is infectious. It pushes you to do more, work harder. And when it rains? You'll find Enrico out on his runs, enjoying the empty streets that most people avoid.

The name "Mami" means "mom" in Italian, and true to form, every tiramisu is made from his mother's authentic recipe. Enrico is wearing The Westwood Linen Blazer, Sienna Neapolitan dress pants & Luxe Voyager tee in white. Check out his look at the link in our bio.

caption:
Iâ€™ve had this nagging feeling over the past year. Somethingâ€™s off when I have my morning muesli with milk, or my favourite walnut + apple overnight oats. And it really came together on that unfortunate evening when I had to abandon my yummm hot chocolate halfway because my stomach just wouldnâ€™t cooperate.

I didnâ€™t understand what was happening. So I started digging into this whole lactose intolerance thing. Am I lactose intolerant? But how could I be when I can comfortably eat paneer, cheese, and dahi? Iâ€™m totally fine with dairy... right?

When I finally did the research, it clicked. What I was experiencing is actually the biological norm for most adults worldwide. Lactose intolerance isnâ€™t binary. Weâ€™re all on a spectrum.

Your tolerance can change over time (like mine apparently did). The amount matters as much as the type (a little milk in tea is okay but a whole glass may not be). And processing makes a huge difference, which is why fermented dairy (where bacteria have already broken down the lactose) works fine for so many of us even when milk doesnâ€™t.

What really surprised me (and made me a bit angry, tbh) was how weâ€™ve built our entire food culture around one populationâ€™s rare genetic mutation. When we looked for data, we couldnâ€™t find many authoritative sources, but smaller studies suggested around two-thirds of South Indians and one-third of North Indians likely have some degree of lactose intolerance. This was news to me!

So if youâ€™ve been in a confusing relationship with milk lately... well, youâ€™re not broken, and youâ€™re in very good (global) company.

Watch the video for the full story.

- Samarth

caption:
Heavy metals are a problem because unlike most things you eat, your body canâ€™t break them down. So over time, they accumulate - in your kidneys, bones, even your brain.

But hereâ€™s what those scary headlines donâ€™t tell you: presence doesnâ€™t mean unsafe.

This is why regulatory safety limits exist. In India, FSSAI says chocolate is safe when it has less than 2.5 mg of lead per kg, and less than 1.5 mg of cadmium per kg. These are based on what our bodies can actually handle.

At TWT, we test every batch of our chocolate against these limits.

So enjoy your chocolate. The simple joy of it far outweighs the minimal risks. Donâ€™t let clickbait steal that from you. ğŸ™‚

Good news. Your favourite bar is back! (ğŸ¥ please)

Introducing our NEW Cranberry Bar. Now with freeze-dried cranberries and raisins.

A few months ago, we told you the whole truth about dried cranberries. That theyâ€™re all candied - soaked in sugar water. Which means hidden added sugar and massive nutrition loss.

So we did the uncomfortable thing. We discontinued the bar. Until we could crack a cleaner way. And thanks to our rockstar product team, now we have.

To understand whatâ€™s different, letâ€™s go to the root cause. Two things. 

One, cranberries are so tart that they need to be sugar-soaked to be palatable. Two, regular drying uses heat, which depletes nutrients.

So how do we solve this?

Enterâ€¦ Freeze-dried cranberries.

This is the same process we use to add mango in our Mango Whey Protein. Itâ€™s simple: the fruit is frozen first, then water is removed in a vacuum. No heat, no nutrient loss. The berry stays tart - but ALL its nutrition stays locked in. Vitamins, minerals, polyphenols - all intact.

But if this is so good, why doesnâ€™t everyone use it?

Well, cost. Freeze-dried cranberries cost around Rs 5000/kg. Regular dried ones are around Rs 500/kg. 10x difference. But itâ€™s the only way to give you real cranberry nutrition without the sugar trap.

But wait. The tartness problem remained. Even freeze-dried cranberries are very tart.

Soâ€¦ enter raisins! Naturally sweet AND tangy. They balance the tartness, add chewy texture, and make the bar yum.

Thatâ€™s it. Months of trial and error to bring this back the right way. Some of you wonâ€™t taste the difference. Some might find it tangier. Some (like us) will just appreciate how gorgeous it looks. (It really does!) What is for sure is that this is nutritionally superior.

Extremely disappointed with the Sun Bath Spray for which I got yesterday. The product I received was clearly used, not new as promised. The packaging was not sealed at all, which is unacceptable for any genuine product. On top of that, almost half of the product was already missing, making it obvious that this item had been opened and used before being sent to me.

Instead of resolving a genuine complaint, they chose to ignore it, which only adds to the frustration. This kind of customer service is unacceptable and reflects how little they care once the payment is done. Overall, this has been a terrible experience from product quality to after-sales support.

caption:
But here is what is equally important to understand.
.
Early puberty is not just about physical changes. It comes with emotional and psychological impact. A child who looks older than her age may still think, feel, and behave like a child. This mismatch can lead to confusion, embarrassment, body image issues, anxiety, or even bullying.

Girls who get their periods early may not fully understand what is happening to their bodies. They may feel scared if no one has prepared them. That is why conversations need to start earlier than we think.

If a girl shows signs of puberty before the age of 8, such as breast development or pubic hair growth, it is important to consult a pediatrician or pediatric endocrinologist. In some cases, early puberty may be linked to underlying medical conditions that need evaluation. In many cases, it may simply be a variation of normal development. But professional guidance helps in making the right call.

As parents, caregivers, and adults, the focus should not be on panic. It should be on preparation.

Talk openly about body changes. Use simple and age appropriate language. Normalize periods before they happen. Teach them that their body is not wrong, not shameful, and not something to hide.

Puberty is not just a biological event. It is a transition. And when it comes early, the support system has to step up earlier too.
Because when her body grows faster than her childhood, she needs information, reassurance, and protection even more.
.

Here is something we want you to remember. 
.
A late period does not automatically mean something is wrong.

Your cycle is deeply connected to your life. Stress from work. Lack of sleep. Travel. Emotional overwhelm. Sudden changes in diet. Intense workouts. Hormonal conditions like PCOS or thyroid imbalance. Even excitement. Your body absorbs it all.

A healthy cycle can range anywhere between 21 to 35 days. And even within that, delays of a few days are common. Your body is not a clock. It is a living system responding to what you are going through.

What matters is the pattern.
If your period is late once in a while, it can be normal.

If it is consistently irregular.

If you are skipping cycles frequently.

If you notice unusual symptoms like sudden weight changes, severe acne, excessive hair growth, or intense cramps.

If there is a chance of pregnancy.

That is when you seek clarity, not panic.

At Sirona, we believe your period is not something to be feared or hidden. It is a powerful indicator of your hormonal health. When it shifts, it is your body communicating.
Track your cycle. Take a pregnancy test if needed. Speak to a gynaecologist when something feels off. Ask questions. Get blood work done if recommended. There is no shame in understanding your own body.
And most importantly, be kind to yourself.
Your body is not betraying you. It is adjusting, responding, surviving, and protecting you every single day.

If your period is late right now, breathe. We are here with you.
.

caption:
Your period can change throughout your life 
.
During your teen years, your body is still figuring out how to regulate your menstrual cycle. This can lead to periods that are irregular and heavy. As you reach your late 20s, your hormones tend to stabilize, leading to a more predictable and potentially lighter flow.

Estrogen and progesterone: These two hormones control the thickening of the lining of your uterus each month. When you ovulate (release an egg), progesterone levels rise. If pregnancy doesnâ€™t occur, progesterone levels drop, triggering your period and the shedding of the uterine lining.
Maturing hormonal balance: As you mature, your body becomes more efficient at regulating these hormones. This can lead to a thinner uterine lining being shed each month, resulting in a lighter flow.

If youâ€™re concerned about any significant changes in your period, itâ€™s always a good idea to talk to your doctor
.
